# Campaign Performance Report
campaign_performance = data.groupby('Campaign ID').agg(
    total_calls=('Call Id', 'count'),
    unique_leads=('Lead Id', 'nunique'),
    calls_connected=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Answered").sum()),
    unique_calls_connected=('Lead Id', lambda x: (data[data['Call Status'] == "Answered"]['Lead Id'].nunique())),
    leads_converted=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Interested").sum()),
    qualified_leads=('Lead Status', lambda x: (x == "Qualified").sum()),
    leads_lost=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Not Interested").sum()),
    avg_agent_call_duration=('Agent Duration(seconds)', 'mean'),
    avg_customer_call_duration=('Customer Duration(seconds)', 'mean')
)

from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA

# Lead Disposition Report
lead_disposition = data['Lead Status'].value_counts()

# Agent Performance Report
agent_performance = data.groupby('Agent Name').agg(
    calls_made=('Call Id', 'count'),
    calls_connected=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Answered").sum()),
    leads_converted=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Interested").sum()),
    avg_agent_call_duration=('Agent Duration(seconds)', 'mean'),
    avg_customer_call_duration=('Customer Duration(seconds)', 'mean')
)

# Convert 'created_at' to numerical data (e.g., timestamps)
data['timestamp'] = data['created_at'].astype(int) / 10**9  # Convert to Unix timestamp in seconds

call_volume_model_fit = call_volume_model.fit()
call_volume_forecast = call_volume_model_fit.forecast(steps=30)

import pandas as pd
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA


# Group by date and calculate agent efficiency metrics
agent_efficiency = data.groupby(pd.Grouper(key='created_at', freq='D')).agg(
    total_calls=('Call Id', 'count'),
    calls_connected=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Answered").sum()),
    avg_agent_call_duration=('Agent Duration(seconds)', 'mean'),
)

# Fit ARIMA models for each agent efficiency metric
arima_total_calls = ARIMA(agent_efficiency['total_calls'], order=(5,1,0))
arima_calls_connected = ARIMA(agent_efficiency['calls_connected'], order=(5,1,0))
arima_avg_agent_call_duration = ARIMA(agent_efficiency['avg_agent_call_duration'], order=(5,1,0))

arima_total_calls_fit = arima_total_calls.fit()
arima_calls_connected_fit = arima_calls_connected.fit()
arima_avg_agent_call_duration_fit = arima_avg_agent_call_duration.fit()

# Forecast agent efficiency metrics for the next 30 days
forecast_steps = 30
forecast_total_calls = arima_total_calls_fit.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)
forecast_calls_connected = arima_calls_connected_fit.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)
forecast_avg_agent_call_duration = arima_avg_agent_call_duration_fit.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)

print("Agent Efficiency Forecast for the next 30 days:")
print("Total Calls Forecast:", forecast_total_calls)
print("Calls Connected Forecast:", forecast_calls_connected)
print("Average Agent Call Duration Forecast:", forecast_avg_agent_call_duration)

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Read the data

# Calculate aggregate metrics for resource allocation
resource_allocation_data = data.groupby('created_at').agg(
    total_calls=('Call Id', 'count'),
    calls_connected=('Call Status', lambda x: (x == "Answered").sum()),
    avg_agent_call_duration=('Agent Duration(seconds)', 'mean'),
    avg_customer_call_duration=('Customer Duration(seconds)', 'mean')
)

# Align features and target variable based on the date index
resource_allocation_data_indexed = resource_allocation_data.reset_index()
y_indexed = data.groupby(data['created_at'].dt.date)['Agent Id'].first().reset_index()
y_indexed['created_at'] = pd.to_datetime(y_indexed['created_at'])  # Convert to datetime64[ns]


# Merge features and target variable based on the date index
resource_allocation_data_merged = pd.merge(resource_allocation_data_indexed, y_indexed, on='created_at')

# Define features and target variable for resource allocation model
X = resource_allocation_data_merged[['total_calls', 'calls_connected', 'avg_agent_call_duration', 'avg_customer_call_duration']]
y = resource_allocation_data_merged['Agent Id']

# Fit linear regression model
resource_allocation_model = LinearRegression()
resource_allocation_model.fit(X, y)


# Forecast the number of agents required for the next 30 days
next_30_days_calls = data['total_calls'].max() + 1  # Assuming constant call volume
next_30_days_calls_connected = data['calls_connected'].max() + 1  # Assuming constant call connection rate
next_30_days_avg_agent_call_duration = resource_allocation_data['avg_agent_call_duration'].mean()  # Assuming constant average agent call duration
next_30_days_avg_customer_call_duration = resource_allocation_data['avg_customer_call_duration'].mean()  # Assuming constant average customer call duration
next_30_days_X = [[next_30_days_calls, next_30_days_calls_connected, next_30_days_avg_agent_call_duration, next_30_days_avg_customer_call_duration]]
next_30_days_agents_required = resource_allocation_model.predict(next_30_days_X)

print("Resource Allocation Forecast (Number of Agents) for the next 30 days:")
print(next_30_days_agents_required)

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load historical call volume data
data['created_at'] = pd.to_datetime(data['created_at'])

# Prepare data for time series forecasting
call_volume = data.groupby(pd.Grouper(key='created_at', freq='D')).size().reset_index(name='calls')
call_volume.set_index('created_at', inplace=True)

# Time series forecasting
model = SARIMAX(call_volume, order=(1, 1, 1), seasonal_order=(1, 1, 1, 7))
results = model.fit()
forecast = results.get_forecast(steps=30)

# Plot historical data and forecast
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(call_volume, label='Historical Call Volume')
plt.plot(forecast.predicted_mean, label='Forecasted Call Volume')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Calls')
plt.title('Call Volume Forecast for Next 30 Days')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Estimate agent capacity
average_calls_per_hour = data['Agent Duration(seconds)'].sum() / (data['Agent Duration(seconds)'].count() * 60)  # Assuming call duration in minutes

# Calculate required agents
forecasted_call_volume = forecast.predicted_mean.sum()
required_agents = forecasted_call_volume / (24 * average_calls_per_hour)  # Assuming 24 hours in a day

print(f"Forecasted Call Volume for Next 30 Days: {forecasted_call_volume}")
print(f"Average Calls Handled per Hour per Agent: {average_calls_per_hour}")
print(f"Estimated Required Agents: {required_agents}")
